text: I was chatting last night with my lady friend about how malevolent Western civilization has become, and _how_ it happened, and how that malevolence is leading to the _destruction_ of Western civilization--almost as if, as Toynbee said, our civilization, like those that have fallen before it, is committing suicide. That's what this movie is talking about when it says we need to change the future.   People are so overt and unapologetic these days about their malevolent behaviour, as if there's no future and it's their way of hastening the destruction of a world and order they know is evil, and that has abused them. If humanity is to have a future, I think people are going have to abandon this retreat into the reptilian brain that was led by neocons, neoliberals, and the religious right, and get back to the strategy that till recent decades has nurtured humanity, and gotten us this far. That is, to reside in the mammalian brain, the sole reason for existing which is to nurture, and in the prefrontal cortex, the sole reason for existing which is to control the reptilian brain. Peace, love, and _understanding_ to everyone...Ôªø

text: I would like to see them make a film adaptation to "Big Thunder Mountain". With the right director and screenwriter, it could be the best live-action Disney movie based on a theme park attraction since the FIRST Pirates of the Caribbean movie (The only good one of the series). Something like Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom/Raiders of the Lost Ark, Prometheus, Pirates of The Caribbean, Congo and to a certain extent The Missing rolled into one! Maybe the story/plot could be about a team of paranormal investigators and scientists embark on a expedition to investigate a Mountain in Utah called "Big Thunder Mountain" that is supposedly haunted and cursed based on a local legend. When they arrive at a the town of Tumbleweed, a small town near Big Thunder Mountain, they meet a mysterious and grizzled yet highly-skilled and wise frontiersman/gunslinger who forewarns them not to up into the mountain, but they ignore his warning. When they do arrive and enter into the mountain, they soon encounter great supernatural horrors and threats and find themselves trapped in the mountain but the same frontiersman they mocked and ignored comes to their rescue and now must trust and depend on him to escape the mountain which turns into a perilous and terrifying quest to not only make it out of the mountain alive but to also save the town of Tumbleweed as well as the rest of the world from a destructive and apocalyptic terror that awaits them as well as free the town of a curse that was brought onto them by the mountain nearly 200 years ago. The threats they encounter while trying to survive the mountain are a undead/zombie-like, and evil tribe of Native American warriors, demonic spirits/entities, inhuman creatures, natural disasters, a ghostly and sinister train, and even a band of evil treasure hunters/bandits seeking for lost Spanish gold buried deep within the mountains.  I think that would make a good idea for a plot for a Big Thunder Mountain movie!

text: All my brothers and sisters in Ferguson, Baltimore, Southside Chicago and Detroit need hope now more than ever; hope for of course"Tomorrow". Twelve Years a Slave, Selma and Belle were good inspirational films but this is the perfect movie to motivate and speak to us all in these pessimistic times, encouraging us to optimistic and never give up; even if you're from the hood.This movie reminds us that if we have no investment, we see no potential, because it's been shut out and hung out to dry. These young people are not lazy. If they were lazy, they wouldn't have gone rioting in the streets, setting fires, tipping over vehicles, smashing windows or looting local businesses when in reality, they were screaming out for help. They don't want to be lazy. They have the potential, they have the drive, they have the passion, they want to show it, they want to express it. But at the end of the day, investment must be the foundation. Flowers and trees can't grow without roots, seeds, water and especially light. We need to shine a light on these communities again. If we invest more and provide more opportunities for these communities, then yes we dare to say that Ferguson, Baltimore, Southside Chicago, and Detroit can be Tomorrowland because we took the effort to be the dreams that we've dreamed of, be the wishes that we've wished for and be the hopes that we've hoped for. So Brothers and sisters, go see this movie! I know you're going to love it, and I hope you take something away from it! Peace! ;)

text: it didn't help this movie to have a thoroughly unlikable protagonist like newton (played by a 25 year old). just a disjointed flick with good intentions, but bizarrely out-of-sync action and, for some reason, murder. i mean, it's like watching a generic teenage dramedy while the characters are being chased by terminators. eh and huh?  maybe it was me because i'm stupid, but the long, rambling speech by dr. house at the end was lost on me. he began babbling, i yawned, and seemed to have gotten lost ~ figuring it didn't matter, i didn't bother rewinding. then all is well and world comes together for everyone apparently except white males, i.e. evil corporate bastards who ruin everything blah blah blah and the world is better off without them.   a feel-good movie that doesn't really give me much to feel good about because it feels so much like it's based in very liberal ideals; that is to say it's got a lot of ideas, but without substance. in the movies, this bullshit world-building works only because it doesn't bother to explain itself, e.g. how an economy works. if you like movies where children basically wind up running the universe, you might get behind this.   for me, not enough tomorowland. not enough tension because of the puzzling plot, which is pretty hard to define easily, imo. the characters, especially newton, are simply not likable. it's actually kind of depressing in parts, but those ideas are the only interesting things about it. it all just feels cobbled together, like trying to say something, but not having the right words.   give a watch, shrug and say 'meh,' and forget about it. you probably won't ever watch it again without having a reason to.
